<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-03-24T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-03-24T13:00:00-05:00" n="527" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d527">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/2009: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Consul at Harbin</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Jenkins</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-03-24T13:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">March 24,
                                        1921—1 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>For Johnson from Stevens.</p>
                        <p>“Your cable March 14th, 7 p.m.<note n="89" xml:id="d527fn89">See
                                telegram, Mar. 14, addressed to the Secretary of State, <ref target="#pg_572">p. 572</ref>.</note> Technical Board must
                            maintain firm stand on all its rights regardless of results. Efforts to
                            have amended Allied agreement giving enlarged complete powers being
                            pushed by Department. You must hold the situation despite
                            intrigues.”</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>